Car warranties sold by the manufacturer are the only way to go if you're going to buy an extended warranty because you can grind the dealer on the price when you buy your new car and usually one repair will cover the cost and the manufacturer backs up the warranty. The third party warranties like endurance and Car Shield are scams. You only need to read the Better Business Bureau complaints or Yelp reviews to see that they never pay. Suckers put out thousands of dollars in premiums and get denied constantly. You're better off just saving your money on an older car and paying for your own repairs. I'd like to add that every new Ford I've ever bought or even Toyota's or Mazdas I've spent about two grand on their best extended warranty if I plan on keeping the car. Almost every single one of them has had a repair far exceeding the cost of that warranty and the manufacturer has always 100% approved the repair with no questions.

Another one that many of you older folks are being pitched is this Colonial Penn nonsense scam insurance. Basically the 9.95 a month gives you about $900 in coverage... but then again people are stupid and don't look into the details , so you're better off just talking to an insurance agent

The golden rule is anything heavily advertised like these cheap insurance plans, gold and silver investments, or extended warranties, including many of these home warranties is a product that will just take your money and never pay out. **How else do you think they can afford to constantly advertise on television?**

Don't be a sucker. Do your research with the Better Business Bureau or Yelp or Google and read all of the reviews including consumer complaints
